# apache-age Best Practices

This document serves as a definitive guide for developers working with Apache AGE. It encompasses best practices for code organization, performance considerations, data modeling, and more, ensuring efficient and maintainable graph database applications.

## Code Organization and Structure

### Use a Modular Approach
Organize your code into modules based on functionality. This enhances readability and maintainability.

❌ BAD
```sql
-- All code in one file
CREATE TABLE users (id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, name VARCHAR(100));
CREATE TABLE posts (id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, content TEXT);
```

✅ GOOD
```sql
-- Separate files for each module
-- users.sql
CREATE TABLE users (id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, name VARCHAR(100));

-- posts.sql
CREATE TABLE posts (id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, content TEXT);
```

### Consistent Naming Conventions
Use consistent naming conventions for tables, columns, and graphs. This aids in understanding and reduces confusion.

❌ BAD
```sql
CREATE TABLE user_data (id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, userName VARCHAR(100));
```

✅ GOOD
```sql
CREATE TABLE users (id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, username VARCHAR(100));
```

## Common Patterns and Anti-patterns

### Use `create_graph()` for Graph Creation
Always use the `create_graph()` function to establish your graph environment. This ensures proper setup and avoids manual errors.

❌ BAD
```sql
-- Manually creating a graph without AGE functions
CREATE TABLE my_graph (id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY);
```

✅ GOOD
```sql
-- Correctly using create_graph()
SELECT create_graph('my_graph');
```

### Avoid Implicit Joins
Explicitly define your joins in queries. This improves readability and performance.

❌ BAD
```sql
SELECT * FROM users, posts WHERE users.id = posts.user_id;
```

✅ GOOD
```sql
SELECT * FROM users
JOIN posts ON users.id = posts.user_id;
```

## Performance Considerations

### Optimize with Indexing
Create indexes on frequently queried columns to enhance performance. Use the `EXPLAIN` command to analyze query plans.

❌ BAD
```sql
-- No indexing
SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = 'john_doe';
```

✅ GOOD
```sql
-- Creating an index
CREATE INDEX idx_username ON users(username);
```

### Use Batch Inserts
When loading large datasets, use batch inserts to minimize overhead.

❌ BAD
```sql
-- Inserting one row at a time
INSERT INTO users (username) VALUES ('user1');
INSERT INTO users (username) VALUES ('user2');
```

✅ GOOD
```sql
-- Batch insert
INSERT INTO users (username) VALUES ('user1'), ('user2');
```

## Common Pitfalls and Gotchas

### Avoid Circular References
Design your graph to avoid circular references, which can lead to infinite loops during traversals.

❌ BAD
```sql
-- Circular reference in relationships
MATCH (a:User)-[:FRIENDS_WITH]->(b:User)-[:FRIENDS_WITH]->(a)
RETURN a, b;
```

✅ GOOD
```sql
-- Properly structured relationships
MATCH (a:User)-[:FRIENDS_WITH]->(b:User)
WHERE a.id <> b.id
RETURN a, b;
```

### Handle Null Values
Always account for potential null values in your queries to prevent unexpected results.

❌ BAD
```sql
SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = NULL;
```

✅ GOOD
```sql
SELECT * FROM users WHERE username IS NULL;
```

## Security Best Practices

### Sanitize User Input
Always sanitize user input to prevent SQL injection attacks. Use parameterized queries wherever possible.

❌ BAD
```sql
-- Directly using user input
EXECUTE 'SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = ''' || user_input || '''';
```

✅ GOOD
```sql
-- Using parameterized queries
PREPARE stmt AS SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = $1;
EXECUTE stmt(user_input);
```

## Query Optimization

### Use `EXPLAIN` for Performance Tuning
Regularly use the `EXPLAIN` command to analyze and optimize your queries.

```sql
EXPLAIN SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = 'john_doe';
```

### Limit Result Sets
Always limit your result sets to avoid excessive data retrieval.

❌ BAD
```sql
SELECT * FROM users;
```

✅ GOOD
```sql
SELECT * FROM users LIMIT 100;
```

## Data Modeling

### Use Appropriate Data Types
Choose the most efficient data types for your columns to save space and improve performance.

❌ BAD
```sql
CREATE TABLE users (id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, age INT);
```

✅ GOOD
```sql
CREATE TABLE users (id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, age SMALLINT);
```

### Normalize Your Data
Normalize your data to reduce redundancy and improve data integrity.

❌ BAD
```sql
CREATE TABLE users (id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, username VARCHAR(100), post_content TEXT);
```

✅ GOOD
```sql
CREATE TABLE users (id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, username VARCHAR(100));
CREATE TABLE posts (id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, user_id INT REFERENCES users(id), content TEXT);
```

By adhering to these best practices, you will enhance the quality, performance, and security of your applications built with Apache AGE.